</tr>
</table>
<p>The <b>Klingon language</b> (<i><b>tlhIngan Hol</b></i> in Klingon) is the <a href="/wiki/Constructed_language" title="Constructed language">constructed language</a> spoken by <a href="/wiki/Klingon" title="Klingon">Klingons</a> in the fictional <a href="/wiki/Star_Trek" title="Star Trek">Star Trek</a> universe. Deliberately designed by <a href="/wiki/Marc_Okrand" title="Marc Okrand">Marc Okrand</a> to be "alien"<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since August 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup>, it contains many peculiarities, such as <a href="/wiki/Object_Verb_Subject" title="Object Verb Subject">Object Verb Subject (OVS)</a> word order. The language's basic sound, along with a few words, was first devised by actor <a href="/wiki/James_Doohan" title="James Doohan">James Doohan</a> ("<a href="/wiki/Montgomery_Scott" title="Montgomery Scott">Scotty</a>") for <i><a href="/wiki/Star_Trek:_The_Motion_Picture" title="Star Trek: The Motion Picture">Star Trek: The Motion Picture</a></i>. That film marked the first time the language had been heard on screen; in all previous appearances, Klingons spoke in English. Klingon was subsequently developed by Okrand into a full-fledged language.</p>
<p>Klingon is sometimes referred to as "Klingonese" (most notably in the <i><a href="/wiki/Star_Trek:_The_Original_Series" title="Star Trek: The Original Series">Star Trek: The Original Series</a></i> episode "<a href="/wiki/The_Trouble_with_Tribbles" title="The Trouble with Tribbles" class="mw-redirect">The Trouble with Tribbles</a>", where it was actually pronounced by a Klingon character as <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/klɪŋgoni/</span>), but among the Klingon-speaking community this is often understood to refer to another Klingon language that is described in <a href="/wiki/John_M._Ford" title="John M. Ford">John M. Ford</a>'s <i>Star Trek</i> novels as <a href="/wiki/Klingonaase" title="Klingonaase">Klingonaase</a>.</p>
<p>A small number of people, mostly dedicated <a href="/wiki/Trekkie" title="Trekkie">Star Trek fans</a> or language aficionados, can converse in Klingon. Its vocabulary, heavily centered on Star Trek-Klingon concepts such as "<a href="/wiki/Klingon_starships" title="Klingon starships">spacecraft</a>" or "<a href="/wiki/Weapons_of_Star_Trek" title="Weapons of Star Trek" class="mw-redirect">warfare</a>", can sometimes make it cumbersome for everyday use&#160;– for instance, while there are words for "transporter ionizer unit" (<i>jolvoy'</i>) or "bridge (of a ship)" (<i>meH</i>), there is currently no word for "bridge" in the sense of a crossing over water. Nonetheless, mundane conversations are common among skilled speakers.</p>
